Secondly, to further study the origin of narrow FWHM emission of CDs, XPS (Fig. 3
                     ) were used to quantitate the chemical structure changes. The full XPS spectra (Fig. 3a, c, e, g)) display three typical peaks at 285, 400, and 532 eV, corresponding to C 1s, N 1s, and O 1s, respectively, demonstrating that all the CDs have the same elemental compositions. In the high-resolution XPS spectra, N 1s spectrum (Fig.3b, d, f, h) shows four peaks at 398.6 eV, 399.4 eV, 400.2 eV, and 401.3 eV, which are attributed to pyridine N, amino N, pyrrole N, and graphite N, respectively [5,13,21]. Through quantitative analysis N1s spectra of CDs prepared by different methods, it can be clearly seen the lowest content (24.55%) of amino N at 399.3 eV for CDs synthesized by the current reported solvent-free and dispersant-free method (CDs-SF, FWHM = 29 nm). In comparison, the contents of amino N are 35.41% for CDs prepared by the literature-reported solvent-free method with boric acid as a dispersant (CDs-H3BO3, FWHM = 42 nm), 36.38% for CDs prepared by solvothermal method in ethanol solution (CDs-EA, FWHM = 45 nm), 37.85% for CDs prepared by solvothermal method at DMF solution (CDs-DMF, FWHM = 44 nm). Obviously, the contents of amino N are positive correlated to FWHM (Table 1
                     , Fig. S3). In comparison, the total oxygen contents for CDs-SF, CDs-EA, CDs-DMF and CDs-H3BO3 are 5.45%, 12.85%, 12.31%, and 6.2% in Fig.3, respectively. Obviously, the contents of oxygen are not correlated to FWHM. Moreover, from the high-resolution O1s spectra of XPS in Fig. S4 in the supporting information, the two components, namely C-O (532.0 eV) and C=O (533.4 eV), are also not correlated to FWHM for CDs-SF, CDs-EA, CDs-DMF, and CDs-H3BO3.
